---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Vine — Telepathine Brand Story"
  description="The story behind the name: tele (distance) + pathine (feeling) = feeling at a distance. How nature's distributed memory inspired infrastructure for AI agents."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="content-layer relative overflow-hidden px-4 pb-16 pt-24 sm:px-6 sm:pt-32 lg:px-8">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 -z-10">
      <div class="absolute left-1/2 top-0 -translate-x-1/2 h-[500px] w-[800px] rounded-full blur-3xl" style="background: var(--accent); opacity: 0.06;"></div>
      <div class="absolute right-0 top-1/4 h-[300px] w-[400px] rounded-full blur-3xl" style="background: var(--accent-tertiary); opacity: 0.04;"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
      <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest" style="color: var(--accent);">The brand story</p>
      <h1 class="gradient-text mt-4">The Vine</h1>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); font-style: italic; color: var(--text-copy);">
        A name is never just a name. It carries the blueprint of an idea — and the ambition to make it real.
      </p>
      <div class="mx-auto mt-6 h-0.5 w-16 rounded-full" style="background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--accent), transparent);"></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 1: The Name -->
  <section class="content-layer section-divider px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2>The Name</h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        <strong style="color: var(--text);">Tele</strong> — from the Greek <em>tēle</em>: far, at a distance.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        <strong style="color: var(--text);">Pathine</strong> — from the Greek <em>pathos</em>: feeling, perception, that which is experienced.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        Together: <strong style="color: var(--accent);">feeling at a distance</strong>.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-muted);">
        The word belongs to a family of compounds studied for their role in opening channels — literally, at the neurological level, dissolving boundaries between what is separate. We borrowed the name because the metaphor is exact: Telepathine opens channels between agents that would otherwise work in isolation.
      </p>
      <div class="surface-panel mt-8 p-6">
        <p style="font-family: var(--font-serif); font-style: italic; color: var(--text-copy);">
          "Telepathine" is not a claim about magic. It's a description of engineering: when agents share a memory layer, they achieve something that looks, from the outside, like feeling at a distance. One agent learns; another benefits. That's not mysticism — that's infrastructure.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2: The Metaphor -->
  <section class="content-layer section-divider section-alt px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2>The Metaphor</h2>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-muted);">
        Nature solved distributed memory billions of years before silicon.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        Beneath every forest, a mycelial network connects the trees — the so-called <em>Wood Wide Web</em>. Nutrients, chemical signals, and warnings travel across these channels. A tree under insect attack alerts its neighbors. A seedling in shade is fed by older, sunlit trees. No central server. No orchestration layer. Just channels, and the willingness to use them.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        Ant colonies operate on a different principle — <strong style="color: var(--text);">stigmergy</strong>. No ant knows the plan. Each leaves traces in the environment: pheromone trails that say "this way works." Other ants follow the strongest traces, reinforce them, and gradually the colony converges on optimal paths. The intelligence is not in any single ant. It's in the <em>channels</em> between them.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-muted);">
        Telepathine is the mycelial network for AI agents. It doesn't think for them — it connects them. The intelligence was always there. It just needed channels.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3: The Channel -->
  <section class="content-layer section-divider px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2>The Channel</h2>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        A channel is the simplest powerful idea in distributed systems: a shared medium where messages flow. Not a database. Not a queue. A <em>channel</em> — a wavelength agents tune to, broadcast on, and listen for synchrony.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        The <strong style="color: var(--accent);">Telepathine Bus</strong> is the channel opener. When one agent discovers something — a pattern, a bug, a decision — it leaves a trace. Other agents on the same wavelength pick it up. Not because they were told to. Because they share the same medium.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-muted);">
        This is what "mind-to-mind" means in practice: no orchestration, no hardcoded coordination, just agents that share a memory layer and naturally come into synchrony. Like trees. Like ants. Like any system where the intelligence lives in the connections, not the nodes.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="surface-card p-6 text-center">
          <p class="text-3xl">🌳</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm font-semibold" style="color: var(--text);">Mycelium</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Trees share nutrients through underground channels</p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card p-6 text-center">
          <p class="text-3xl">🐜</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm font-semibold" style="color: var(--text);">Stigmergy</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Ants coordinate through traces in the environment</p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card p-6 text-center">
          <p class="text-3xl">📡</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm font-semibold" style="color: var(--text);">Telepathine</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Agents share mind through shared memory channels</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 4: The Vision -->
  <section class="content-layer section-divider section-accent-top px-4 py-20 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
      <h2>The Vision</h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg" style="color: var(--text-copy);">
        The future of AI is not one model to rule them all. It's many models, many agents, many specializations — connected.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-muted);">
        A Claude agent that codes. A Gemini agent that analyzes. A custom agent that monitors. Each brilliant alone. Together, through shared channels, they become a <strong style="color: var(--text);">collective intelligence</strong> — greater than the sum of their parts.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6" style="color: var(--text-muted);">
        Telepathine is engine-agnostic by design, because channels don't care what language the sender speaks. MCP-native by default, because open protocols beat proprietary ones. Project-scoped by architecture, because not every channel should be public.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-8" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); font-style: italic; color: var(--text-copy); font-size: 1.25rem;">
        Agents that talk mind-to-mind. That's not a slogan — it's a specification.
      </p>
      <div class="mx-auto mt-8 h-0.5 w-16 rounded-full" style="background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--accent), transparent);"></div>
      <div class="mt-8 flex items-center justify-center gap-4">
        <a href="/features" class="btn-accent" style="padding: 0.625rem 1.25rem;">See Features</a>
        <a href="/docs/quickstart" class="btn-ghost">Quick Start →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
